abstract: NEW-HAVEN, Conn., Aug. 2 -- The forty-eighth annual cruise of the New-York Yacht Club began to-day. A fleet of about eighty yachts was at anchor in Hempstead Harbor off Glen Cove at 11:15 this morning to greet the flapship Electra as she came to anchor. abstract: CHICAGO, Ang. 23 -- The cattle trade had a very dull opening to-day, and the close was little better. Receipts were 9,000 head. abstract: HAMBURG, Aug. 23 -- The warning conveyed in these dispatches yesterday that the so-called cholerine prevailing in this city would bear watching on the part of the United States immigration authorities has received official justification. To-day the authorities in this city, in response to inquiries made by the American Consul here relative to the character of the disease, admitted that it was true Asiatic cholera.

abstract: NEWPORT, R.I., Aug. 27. -- The storm to-day put a stop to all outdoor entertainments. The cold was keenly felt, so that overcoats and wood fires were in general demand. The Narragansett Pler and Block Island boats both attempted to make their regular trips, but were obliged to return on account of the heavy sea. Under the circumstances Mrs. George Peabody Wetmore's entertainment was a delightful success and the dinner one to be long remembered.

The latter was favorite at odds; and at the end of five heats the race was awarded to him. But the majority of horsemen were of the opinion that the race should have gone to Steve Whipple.

abstract: From Good Words. As the evidence of the earth's crust proves that our globe has lasted for incalculable ages, it becomes of interest to think how far the gradual elongation of the day may have attained significant proportions since very early times.
